tion": "BDKRB2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9864321947097778, "span": {"begin": 834, "end": 840}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3558"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9725514054298401, "span": {"begin": 901, "end": 905}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-6", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9696215391159058, "span": {"begin": 907, "end": 911}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3576"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-8", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9424938559532166, "span": {"begin": 916, "end": 920}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4790"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFKb", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9912671446800232, "span": {"begin": 990, "end": 994}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7124"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TNF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8937621712684631, "span": {"begin": 1054, "end": 1057}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3552"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9493365287780762, "span": {"begin": 1062, "end": 1065}}], "text": "Bradykinin (BK) plays an important role in the kinin-kallikrein system (KKS) as a regulator of blood pressure and can induce vasodilation, increase blood flow, as well as hypotension. BK is also an important part of the inflammatory process after injury, induces&nbsp;pain stimulation, and increases&nbsp;vascular permeability (Maas, 10.1007/s12016-016-8540-0).   The bradykinin system gets activated through various methods, including nanoparticles and SARS-COV-2 via the contact activation system (Maas, 10.1007/s12016-016-8540-0, Ekdahl doi: 10.1080/14686996.2019.1625721). Activation of the bradykinin system leads to increase of proinflammatory mediators due to increased production of proinflammatory mediator bradykinin(https://doi.org/10.1161/01.CIR.95.5.111 &nbsp;as well as upregulating bradykinin receptor 1 (BDKRB1) and 2(BDKRB2), leading to induction of proinflammatory mediators such as IL-2, IL-6 and IL-8 (https://doi.org/10.1165/rcmb.2002-0040OC) and the activation of the NFKb pathway leading to production of proinflammatory mediators TNF and IL1(https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:34:33 +0000 2026"}